          <source>How to: Animate an Object Along a Path (Point Animation)</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>How to: Animate an Object Along a Path (Point Animation)</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This example shows how to use a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.PointAnimationUsingPath&gt;</ph> object to animate a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Point&gt;</ph> along a curved path.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example moves an <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry&gt;</ph> along a path defined by a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.PathGeometry&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The ellipse geometry's <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry.Center%2A&gt;</ph> property, which takes a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Point&gt;</ph> value, specifies its position; to move the ellipse geometry, you animate its <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry.Center%2A&gt;</ph> property.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The example uses a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.PointAnimationUsingPath&gt;</ph> to animate the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry&gt;</ph> object's <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry.Center%2A&gt;</ph> property.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For the complete sample, see <bpt id="p1">[</bpt>Path Animation Sample<ept id="p1">](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=160028)</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The code version of the preceding sample used a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Storyboard&gt;</ph> to animate the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.EllipseGeometry&gt;</ph>, even though only one animation was applied.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Storyboard&gt;</ph> is often the easiest way to apply multiple animations because these animations can be controlled by the same <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Storyboard&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>However, an easier way to apply a single animation to a property when using code is to use the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.Animatable.BeginAnimation%2A&gt;</ph> method.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
